{# ══ Activity 1 — Causal Fallacies ══════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(1, "Causal Fallacies — Correlation is Not Causation", "arrow-right-circle") %}
<p>
  Causal fallacies (also called <em>non causa pro causa</em> — "not the cause for the cause")
  occur when a connection between events is mistaken for a causal relationship.
  Establishing genuine causation requires more than identifying a correlation.
</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u08-causal">

  {% call accordion("c01", "Post Hoc Ergo Propter Hoc — 'after this, therefore because of this'") %}
  <p>Assuming that because one event followed another, the first caused the second.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "I started wearing a lucky bracelet, and since then I have not had a cold. The bracelet is preventing illness."
  </p>
  <p style="color:#ddd; font-size:0.87rem;">
    Temporal sequence (A before B) is necessary for causation but not sufficient. Many things happen before many other things without causing them.
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("c02", "Cum Hoc Ergo Propter Hoc — 'with this, therefore because of this'") %}
  <p>Assuming that two things that occur together are causally related. This is the classic correlation-causation confusion.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "Ice cream sales and drowning rates both increase in summer. Ice cream causes drowning."
  </p>
  <p style="color:#ddd; font-size:0.87rem;">
    Both are caused by a third variable (hot weather), not by each other.
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("c03", "False Cause — general causal error") %}
  <p>Any error in which a non-causal relationship is treated as causal. This is the umbrella term for all causal fallacies.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "Countries with more television sets per household have higher life expectancy. Therefore, buying more televisions increases life expectancy."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("c04", "Slippery Slope — unwarranted causal chain") %}
  <p>Claiming that if one event is allowed to occur, a chain of increasingly bad consequences will inevitably follow — without justifying why each step in the chain is necessary.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "If we allow students to retake one exam, soon they will expect to retake every assessment, and eventually grades will become meaningless."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

</div>

<h5 class="mt-4" style="color:#ff8c00;">Post Hoc in action — video</h5>
<p>Watch this clip illustrating <em>post hoc ergo propter hoc</em> reasoning in a US television drama.</p>
