{# ══ Activity 2 — Weak Evidence Fallacies ════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(2, "Weak Evidence Fallacies", "bar-chart-line") %}
<p>
  These fallacies involve using evidence that is technically present but insufficient
  to support the conclusion drawn.
</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u08-weak">

  {% call accordion("w01", "Hasty Generalisation — too small a sample") %}
  <p>Drawing a broad conclusion from a sample that is too small or unrepresentative to support it.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "I met two people from that city who were rude. People from that city are rude."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("w02", "Anecdotal — personal experience as general evidence") %}
  <p>Using a personal experience or a single isolated case in place of systematic evidence.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "My grandfather smoked every day and lived to 95. Smoking cannot be that dangerous."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("w03", "Texas Sharpshooter — cherry-picking data") %}
  <p>
    Selecting data that supports a predetermined conclusion while ignoring the rest.
    The name comes from a mythical shooter who fires at a barn, then draws a target
    around the bullet holes.
  </p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "This dietary supplement has been tested 100 times. In 6 trials it outperformed the placebo — proof that it works." (The arguer ignores the 94 trials showing no effect.)
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("w04", "Unrepresentative Sample — biased sampling") %}
  <p>Drawing conclusions from a sample that does not reflect the population being studied.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "Our survey of 500 social media users found that 90% support this policy. The public overwhelmingly supports it." (Social media users are not a representative sample of the general public.)
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("w05", "Misleading Statistics — inappropriate use of data") %}
  <p>Using statistics as evidence when they are biased, cherry-picked, or inapplicable to the claim.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "Our new drug reduces the risk of heart attack by 50%." (The risk fell from 2% to 1% — a 50% relative reduction, but only a 1% absolute reduction in real terms.)
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

</div>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 3 — Circular and Linguistic Fallacies ══════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(3, "Circular and Linguistic Fallacies", "arrows-angle-contract") %}

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u08-other">

  {% call accordion("o01", "Begging the Question (Circular Reasoning) — assuming the conclusion") %}
  <p>Including the conclusion in the premises — or assuming what needs to be proved.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "This book must be true because it says so, and what it says is always true."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("o02", "Burden of Proof — shifting the burden") %}
  <p>Claiming that the burden of proof lies with the person disputing a claim, rather than with the person making it. The principle: extraordinary claims require extraordinary evidence; the burden falls on the claimant.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "Prove that this herbal supplement does not cure cancer. Until you can, I will continue to take it."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("o03", "Loaded Question — a question with a built-in assumption") %}
  <p>A question that presupposes a claim which the respondent has not accepted. Any answer to the question appears to confirm the presupposition.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "Have you stopped cheating on your expenses?" (Answering either yes or no implies the person has cheated.)
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("o04", "Ambiguity — equivocation") %}
  <p>Using a word or phrase with more than one meaning and shifting between meanings within an argument.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "The sign said 'fine for parking here.' So I parked there." (The sign uses "fine" to mean a penalty; the driver interprets it as permission.)
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("o05", "Appeal to Nature — natural = good") %}
  <p>Arguing that because something is natural, it is therefore good, safe, or preferable — and that artificial things are bad.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "This product is completely natural, so it has no side effects." (Arsenic and botulinum toxin are natural; many life-saving medicines are synthetic.)
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("o06", "Middle Ground — false compromise") %}
  <p>Assuming that a compromise between two positions must be correct. Sometimes the truth is not in the middle — one side may simply be right.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "You say climate change is driven by humans; the other side says it is entirely natural. The truth must be somewhere in the middle."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("o07", "Personal Incredulity — I don't understand it, therefore it's false") %}
  <p>Claiming that because you cannot understand how something works, it is probably not true or impossible.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "I cannot understand how vaccines train the immune system, so I don't believe they work."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("o08", "Gambler's Fallacy — independence of random events") %}
  <p>Believing that past random events affect the probability of future independent events. Each spin of a roulette wheel is independent of all previous spins.</p>
  <p style="color:#aaa; font-size:0.87rem; font-style:italic;">
    "The coin has landed heads ten times in a row. It is bound to be tails next time."
  </p>
  {% endcall %}

</div>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 4 — Spot the Fallacy ══════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(4, "Spot the Fallacy", "search") %}
<p>
  Identify the informal fallacy in each passage. Use both Unit 7 and Unit 8 fallacies.
</p>

<ol style="color:#ddd; line-height:1; margin-bottom:1rem;">
  <li style="margin-bottom:1.4rem; line-height:1.8;">
    "Organic food is natural, which means it is healthier than conventional food with its artificial pesticides."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom:1.4rem; line-height:1.8;">
    "Kaoru started drinking coffee when she joined Professor X's lab. Twenty years later, Kaoru became a world-famous researcher. This proves the positive effect of drinking coffee on academic achievement."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom:1.4rem; line-height:1.8;">
    "Prove to me that extraterrestrial life does not exist. Until you can do so, you have no reason to disbelieve it."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom:1.4rem; line-height:1.8;">
    "This new drug reduces stroke risk by 40%!" (In fact, the stroke rate fell from 0.5% to 0.3%.)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom:1.4rem; line-height:1.8;">
    "The coin has come up heads eight times in a row. I should definitely bet on tails this time."
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom:1.4rem; line-height:1.8;">
    "The Bible is the word of God because it says so in the Bible, and the Bible is true because it is the word of God."
  </li>
</ol>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="u08-spot">
  {% call accordion("spot-08", "Reveal the answers") %}
  <ol style="color:#ddd; font-size:0.88rem; line-height:2.3;">
    <li><strong>Appeal to Nature</strong> — "natural" does not mean safe or beneficial. Many natural substances are harmful; many synthetic ones are beneficial.</li>
    <li><strong>Post Hoc Ergo Propter Hoc</strong> — the coffee drinking preceded her success, but that does not establish it as the cause. Many other factors contributed to her career.</li>
    <li><strong>Burden of Proof</strong> — the burden of proof lies with the person making the claim, not with those who remain sceptical. "You cannot disprove it" is not evidence for it.</li>
    <li><strong>Misleading Statistics</strong> — a 40% relative reduction sounds dramatic, but the absolute reduction is only 0.2 percentage points (from 0.5% to 0.3%). The relative framing exaggerates the effect size.</li>
    <li><strong>Gambler's Fallacy</strong> — each coin flip is an independent event. Past results have no influence on future outcomes for a fair coin.</li>
    <li><strong>Begging the Question (Circular Reasoning)</strong> — the Bible's authority is assumed to prove its own truth, and its truth is assumed to establish its authority. The argument goes in a circle.</li>
  </ol>
  {% endcall %}
</div>
{% endcall %}


